This year‚Äôs report focuses on the emerging role of AI in the workplace. See link in bio for the full report. 

One of the key findings? We have too much to do, and too little time to do it all. We‚Äôre drowning in a deep sea of digital debt: data, emails, meetings, and chats. We can‚Äôt tread water fast enough to stay afloat, and it‚Äôs costing us time, energy, and innovation. Microsoft‚Äôs research finds:
-¬†64% of employees don‚Äôt have enough time and energy to get their work done, and those employees are 3.5x more likely to say they struggle with being innovative.
-¬†The average person spends 57% of their time communicating and only 43% creating (based on time spent in Microsoft 365)
-¬†68% of people say they don‚Äôt have enough focus time, and the #1 productivity disruptor is inefficient meetings

We need a meetings makeover! How can we stop sinking? Block out time for deep thinking. We should think of our time more like cake than confetti (Schulte, 2014)‚Äîinstead of letting our days be torn to shreds, we should proactively plan and protect blocks for deep, individual work, as well as for ‚Äúbursty‚Äù collaborations that allow us to communicate and respond quickly (Riedl & Woolley, 2018). It all comes down to paying attention to our attention‚Äîchoosing to spend our time on the things that matter and give us energy.

If you don‚Äôt already know, I am a huge History nerd and even got my degree in it at King‚Äôs. ‚Å£
‚Å£
I firmly believe that to understand where we are today and to move towards a better future we have to have a firm grasp of the past and the events that led us to where we are, and who we are, today. ‚Å£
‚Å£
So, when @microsoft asked me to experience the ‚ÄòAncient Olympia: Common Grounds‚Äô exhibition at the Athens Olympic Museum, I couldn‚Äôt say no, and truly had the most amazing time! ‚Å£
‚Å£
I remember watching Kelly Holmes and the men‚Äôs 4x100m at the Athens Games in 2004 and it was at that moment I knew that I wanted to compete in the games - to be part of that community and legacy of sporting excellence that started thousands of years ago. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Putting on the Microsoft HoloLens 2 instantly immersed me into Ancient Olympia where it stood 2,000 years ago ü§Ø The mixed reality technology brought to life the ancient running track (which looked very long - deffo like over 200m in a straight line üòÆ‚Äçüí® - would not have been amused if that was my discipline lol), the Statue of Zeus, and I even got to hold some of the structures in the palm of my hand! ‚Å£
‚Å£
It was amazing to have been transported to the ancient origins of the modern Games; a UNESCO world heritage site ü•π‚Å£
‚Å£
My 8 year old self loved it, the History nerd in me loved it, and of course as a professional athlete and medalist, I felt so very connected to the roots of what we do and our place in History. Grateful for an incredible experience that meant so much to me ‚ù§Ô∏è #microsoftpartner

Virgil Abloh wasn‚Äôt just a fashion designer, an architect, or a revolutionary creative collaborator. He was a dreamer from the outside of Chicago that showed us what can be possible. Being all those things and more, Virgil purposefully lived an open-source life ‚Äî sharing his life learnings which he titled as ‚ÄúCODES‚Äù to positively impact our culture.

As we continue to unpack his legacy, we‚Äôve invited some of Virgil‚Äôs closest collaborators and friends, to share the ‚ÄúCODES‚Äù they‚Äôve learned from him in a six-part series. Kiki is a member of J pod, a close-knit family of 24 endangered Southern Resident orca whales, and she‚Äôs 6-years-old. 
.
Using the HoloLens2, audiences are immersed in an underwater experience and connect with J pod and Kiki to experience the power of echolocation, used by orcas to communicate and hunt. Noise pollution from human activity is disrupting that sonic ability, blinding the orcas in their search for food. This experience is the intersection between the story of a family's survival, how we rethink conservation, and how we engage with technology to create impact. Check out our Story for more.

The TSU Tigerbelles are known for the world records they broke, the style they pioneered, and the activism they inspired. Now, their legacy is the subject of an exhibit at the @ncrmuseum in Memphis, TN.

To celebrate the Tigerbelles, Nike commissioned an art installation‚Äîcomposed of over 20,000 track spikes‚Äîfor display at the museum. Together with the museum, we also hosted multiple generations of Tigerbelles for a once-in-a-lifetime event to unveil the piece, bringing together 60-plus years of Tigerbelle history together in one room.

Can 25,984 track spikes tell the story of a running dynasty? We hope so.

To celebrate the HBCU Tennessee State University‚Äôs female track team, the Tigerbelles, Nike partnered with @ncrmuseum for a larger-than-life art installation, depicting a famous photograph of track athletes Debbie Jones, Chandra Cheeseborough and Ernestine Davis crossing a finish line in 1978.

That year, the Tigerbelles set the World Record in the 880-yard indoor relay, the first-ever set by a Nike-sponsored team, collegiate or professional. Their story needs to be known, far and wide, because the Tigerbelles would change running‚Äîand athlete activism‚Äîforever.

Head to the link in our bio to learn more about the Tigerbelles.

Introducing our 2022 Yardrunners, otherwise known as the student leaders and alumni who continue to build upon a legacy of Black excellence at Historically Black Colleges and Universities. What legacy means to them is completely unique, as it was to the generation before and will be for the GOATs of tomorrow.

Nike #Yardrunners was created in 2020 to celebrate the rich heritage, history, and contributions of HBCUs and their alumni on global sport and culture. Founded by Nike HBCU alumni, each year the initiative serves as an opportunity for teams at Nike to partner with HBCU trailblazers to create inspirational storytelling and philanthropy with and for the community.

Eliud Kipchoge is the most decorated marathon runner in the history of the sport. But he is running for more than accolades‚Äîhe is running for humanity. Two days after his record-setting win in Tokyo, we caught up with Eliud in Kaptagat, Kenya and captured an intimate look at his life away from sport: spending quality time with his family, going for runs on the red clay roads near his home, and tending to his nearby farm. Through his platform and the on-the-ground efforts of his foundation, Eliud is focused on ensuring that the land he runs through remains clean and safe for next generation of runners.

Never Done chasing the finish line.

University students in Japan prepare all year for Ekiden, a relay marathon race that takes place on the mountainous roads surrounding Tokyo. These men and women channel a tunnel vision of optimism and teamwork to compete in these prestigious races.

As they run in fellowship and sweat side by side, many Japanese people huddle in warmth inside their homes and lean in to eagerly watch the races and celebrate the New Year.

In Japan many athletes who competed in the summer games started at one point as an Ekiden runner. As they welcome the new year they will soon have another task, to pass the baton to the next generation of Ekiden runners.

It takes a village to raise a team.

In a hidden village in Marfa, Texas, lies a team of dedicated administrators, fans, and coaches who keep the spirit of the game alive by coming together to play Six-Man Football. After a grueling period during the Great Depression, a Nebraska coach invented a high-scoring adaptation of traditional football by cutting six players to accommodate dwindling populations in rural towns. A booming art scene has skyrocketed the cost of living and continued to drive out long-time locals, but the sport hasn‚Äôt just kept kids on the field; it‚Äôs kept this community more unified than ever.

What sport bonds your community?
